\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 Before you use WinVN to read news, you must give it the information it needs to contact the {\ul news server}{\v news_server}, send {\uldb electronic mail}{\v electronic_mail_message}
, and so on.   In addition, you can configure WinVN with personal preferences, such as the colors and fonts it uses, how many article titles should be automatically fetched at once, and so on.  
\par All configuration commands are accessible from the Config menu of the {\uldb main window}{\v main_window}.  See {\uldb Config Menu Commands}{\v config_menu_commands}.
\par By default, configuration information is written to the file {\f7 WINVN.INI}{\f4  in the current directory}{\f7 .}  The curious may wish to examine this file with a text editor.  See {\uldb Invoking WinVN}{\v invoking_winvn}.
\par \pard\plain \s254\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320 \b\f8\lang1033 \page {\plain \f8\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Invoking WinVN}} {\plain \f8\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} Invoking_WinVN}} {\plain \f8\fs18\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 K} command line}} Invoking WinVN
\par \pard\plain \s10\li120\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 K} Configuring WinVN}}
 WinVN is typically invoked by double-clicking on an icon in Program Manager; however, WinVN can be invoked via the {\b File/Run...} menu command or by any other mechanism that can be used to start a Windows program.
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 When WinVN starts, it looks for two files:  WINVN.INI{\fs18\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 K} WINVN.INI}}
 , which contains configuration and customization information, and {\uldb NEWSRC}{\v newsrc}.{\fs18\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 K} newsrc}}  By default, WinVN looks in the current directory for thes
e files.  However, there are ways of specifying alternate locations for these files.
\par \pard\plain \s253\li120\sb120\sa60\sl-240 \b\f8\fs20\lang1033 WINVN Command Line
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 You can pass command line arguments to WinVN to tell it where to locate your WINVN.INI and NEWSRC files.  The format of the command line is:
\par    WINVN  IniFile  NewsrcFile
\par         or
\par    WINVN  Path
\par In the first case, WinVN will take IniFile to be the filename--including path specification--of the initialization file.  If IniFile is just a directory name, WinVN will look for the file named WINVN.INI in that directory.  Similarly, WinVN takes the seco
nd argument, NewsrcFile, as a filename for the news history file.  If NewsrcFile is just a directory name, WinVN will look for the file named NEWSRC in that directory.
\par If, as in the second case, WinVN is run with one argument, WinVN will use it as a directory name for both the WINVN.INI and NEWSRC files.
\par (Actually, this is a simplified description of how WinVN searches for these files.  For a complete description, curious readers are referred to the source code file {\f7 ini}{\f7 \_}{\f7 news.c}.)
\par \pard\plain \s253\li120\sb120\sa60\sl-240 \b\f8\fs20\lang1033 WINVN Environment Variable
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 Alternatively, you can set an environment variable to
 tell WinVN where to look for these two files.  Set the environment variable WINVN to the directory in which both the WINVN.INI and NEWSRC files can be found.  For instance:
\par {\f7    SET WINVN=F:}{\f7 \\}{\f7 FRED}
\par The WinVN environment variable must be set before windows starts up.  Every DOS shell within Windows maintains its own seperate copy of the environment.  Windows only looks at the environment that existed at startup.  
\par On a PC LAN, an administrator can add code in the login script to set the WINVN environment var
iable to the unique location of a user's WINVN.INI file (on a network drive).  For those using multiple news servers, you can have multiple icons from within Windows and they have command line arguments set.
\par \pard\plain \s253\li120\sb120\sa60\sl-240 \b\f8\fs20\lang1033 Summary of WinVN's Search for WINVN.INI and NEWSRC
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f8\fs20\lang1033 Winvn uses the following search mechanism to find the WINVN.INI file:
\par           Command line    (e.g.,   {\f7 n:}{\f7 \\}{\f7 winvn}{\f7 \\}{\f7 winvn.exe u:}{\f7 \\}{\f7 winvn.ini u:}{\f7 \\}{\f7 newsrc})
\par           WINVN Environment variable
\par           Application startup directory
\par           Windows Directory
\par           Windows System Directory
\par           DOS search path
